  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4088330307" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4088330307" />
    <a title="Michael Battaglia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17248131-michael-battaglia"><img alt="Michael Battaglia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1360285538p2/17248131.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4088330307?book_show_action=true">Jul 29, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Battaglia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Battaglia" href="/user/show/17248131-michael-battaglia">Michael Battaglia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4088330307" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8130944186539469184">Isaac Babel&apos;s life is one of those stories that makes you angry and despairing and weirdly hopeful all at the same time, though for different reasons. One of the most famous (if not the) most famous Russian Jewish writers of his time, he spent a good chunk of the 1920s writing story after story that were well received by the public, especially his &quot;Red Cavalry&quot; stories and the Odessa Tales, both of which had a kind of realism that was a bit of a new style for the time. He also kept himself busy </span>
  <span id="freeText8130944186539469184" style="display:none">Isaac Babel's life is one of those stories that makes you angry and despairing and weirdly hopeful all at the same time, though for different reasons. One of the most famous (if not the) most famous Russian Jewish writers of his time, he spent a good chunk of the 1920s writing story after story that were well received by the public, especially his "Red Cavalry" stories and the Odessa Tales, both of which had a kind of realism that was a bit of a new style for the time. He also kept himself busy with a couple of plays and at least one movie script that had his name removed for reasons that will become clear in a moment (it was Mark Donskoi's Gorky trilogy). He also somehow found time in his busy schedule to start a second family, with his wife living in Paris and his mistress living in Moscow.<br /><br />By the 1930s the Russian government was getting a little less friendly with writers who thought they could write whatever they wanted and there was serious danger in the air. Babel went back to Russia anyway (asking his estranged wife and daughter to come with him, a refusal that wound up being somewhat prescient, although drawing a line between "Stalinist Russia" and "bad things happening to people" doesn't require that much of a burst of insight) and before too long was arrested by the NKVD for whatever made-up reason the Soviet government thought sounded good. Needless to say, by all reports his stay in prison was less than pleasant, involving interrogations and torture, probably not in that order (or simultaneously, since oppressive governments seem to value multi-tasking), eventually culminating in a trial with a predetermined outcome. It should come to no one's surprise that the sentence was death and though Babel pleaded with his captors to "let me finish my work" the only response he got was a bullet to the head and his ashes in a common grave. A year later the Soviets managed to get around to telling everyone he had died in prison, getting the date completely wrong, and conveniently leaving out all the stuff about torture and execution. It wasn't until the mid-1950s that the Khrushchev government got the story straight with a typed statement that comes thisclose to saying "Oops", basically claiming that "new evidence" had come to light, giving them a reason to revoke the sentence, as if it hadn't been clear all along that he was essentially murdered because the government decided they didn't like him.<br /><br />Fortunately, a not-insubstantial number of people had refused to forget about him. With the Russian government finally admitting that, oh gee, maybe he wasn't a criminal after all, it paved the way for new volumes of his works to appear, although some were still censored. Finally in the 2000s uncensored complete volumes appeared, including translated versions in English, with his daughter Nathalie and others being instrumental in compiling the more recent volumes. At this point just about all his major stories are still in print in various volumes, along with some unpublished works (although it came out later that the Russian government had burned the unfinished manuscripts they had seized when he was arrested, just to compound the tragedy) . . . the one I have is titled "Collected Stories" and doesn't appear to be available anymore, having been replaced with a "Complete Works" that probably includes material like his plays and whatnot that aren't covered here.<br /><br />So this one just covers his short stories (he never finished any novels, though some stories toward the end seem to be test runs for novels he was working on) although at nearly five hundred pages there's enough here to keep you busy for a while. What might impress you is how many stories they're able to cram into those hundreds of pages, assisted by the fact that Babel is a surprisingly dense writer. Most of the stories are only a handful of pages long and they whip by with an astonishing speed, often seeming to begin on the downstroke, already in motion and ending even before you have a real chance to figure out what just happened, leaving only a stirring of dust to remind you that something has just passed through. There are times when it can make for a bewildering experience, because as good as Babel was, he was a man very much immersed in his time and place, steeped in current and past events (his Red Cavalry stories stemmed from his time as a journalist assigned to the army), the stories layered with details and sly criticisms that would have probably made perfect sense to the average Russian of the time but modern readers who aren't steeped in context might find themselves a bit at sea at times.<br /><br />The going is slightly easier in the earlier stories, before Babel really hit his stride. He's still figuring out his style and a lot of them are slices of life that often end on a despairing shrug, as if everything isn't destined to necessarily get worse but be just like the day before and the day before that, an unending sea of grey where the only difference is perhaps a slight change in the shadings. But even that might be your eyes. He's got a good eye for sobering detail without going overboard (the matter of fact and offscreen abortion in "Mamma, Rimma, and Alla", followed by a letter that says everything in the negative spaces) or can sketch out a character's life without using much space (the nurse in "Doudou", all of two pages!) but more often than not the stories are shards of blunt impact, spitting out words as if too hot to handle and then ducking out before they're consumed completely. Its these spitfires that first brought him notice and there is a raging passion to these stories that later, longer stories can't quite match, just the feel of someone who has to get the story down as quickly as possible before it vaporizes entirely.<br /><br />The Red Cavalry stories were his real breakthrough and to say that Russian public wasn't entirely ready for these is understating matters slightly. Taken from his diaries, Babel presents a series of loosely linked stories (many seem to have the same unnamed narrator, who seems to be a writer) that are sometimes staggering in how brutally honest they are about events he witnessed. Taking place during the Polish-Soviet War, it mostly underscores how much of a mess things were in the aftermath of World War One, with Russian descending into civil war (between the Red Army and White Army) with Poland using the distraction to take some territory. Once Lenin's crew got around to finishing off the White Army, they decided that immediately starting another war was a good idea and thus everyone spent the next two years trying to kill each other, something that never seemed to get old in the 20th century. Unfortunately for Lenin, the Red Armies got crushed but unfortunately for the Polish they never made a decisive blow and thus didn't quite achieve their aims either.<br /><br />Babel's stories sugarcoat absolutely nothing and what's sometimes surprising is how direct they are in their brutalities. The dead are scattered everywhere, everyone is wounded or about to get wounded and nothing seems to be going well. These are bleak stories from someone who seems to be constantly appalled at everything going on around him, aware that these events have been set in motion and nothing can stop them, leaving him only as a kind of witness to how badly people can treat each other. As I mentioned earlier the stories have a linked feel to them, a staccato sense of a war flashing before someone eyes in blaring images . . . Babel's tendency to get in and get out fast causes the tales to sort of roll into each other, like you're overhearing conversations at warp speed (this is where his habit of writing like the tape started rolling five minutes before the story starts on the page can be particularly punishing). This can cause some confusion, because the stories seem to assume that you're the average Russian reader of the 1920s and these are all current events to you. The footnotes help alleviate some of that but a lot of the finer details (like when Babel uses real people in his stories, sometimes in ways that didn't make them very happy with him) I know eluded me as early 20th century Russian history is definitely a blind spot in my reading. So that may blunt the stories' impact slightly but even with the stuff that doesn't need a degree in history to figure out he gives you quite a bit to chew on. Borges was a fan of "Salt" (a letter home written with some shockingly bloodthirsty zeal) but there's a lot to choose from here, where they all blend into a texture that's utterly chilling (Babel especially makes it clear that as much as the armies hated each other, neither of them were very fond of the Jews) in how he spits out what could be variations of the same scenario but turns it all into a floor covered in bloodstained glass that everyone can't stop dancing on. Eventually its slick with blood and all the blood looks the same, even if every inch holds a different disaster.<br /><br />The Red Cavalry stories are really no one's idea of a good time, even if there are some moments of dark, dark humor, but the Odessa Stories are a little lighter. Granted, its somewhat relative being they still take place in a less than ideal period of Russian history and are mostly comprised of tales of Jewish gangsters doing what gangsters do best . . . making life great for themselves and miserable for everyone else. Recurring character Benya Krik is probably the most colorful fellow you'll find in the book (the character was later the subject of a 1926 silent film), starting from the get-go with establishing story "The King" which manages to cram both a wedding and a bit of brash arson into its few pages. It basically sets the tone for everything that's going to come after and what Babel excels at here is really giving Odessa a sense of place . . . even if the stories are fictional the city itself breathes, a skittering sense of people trying to survive by any means necessary, even if those means aren't necessarily legal. The tales feel propulsive, surging from one to the next without stopping to even catch a breath, making people who are doing less than pleasant things feel like real people, just doing what it takes, even if they're willing to go a little further than everyone around them. For me, this is where Babel started to feel poetic as well, with knowing turns of phrases delivered by people who have already seen too much and know its still not over yet (there's a pair of lines from "Waiting for Godot" that seems to capture the feel of some of these: "I can't go on like this." "That's what you think."). But there's a sense of wounded humanity to all of them that gives them a weird power . . . in a way they're easier to relate to than the Red Cavalry stories, even if those have a more visceral impact.<br /><br />After those two sets of stories Babel started to get more autobiographical, with the end result being longer story that are a bit more ruminative. They lack of a bit of the wild fire of the earlier stuff but on some level hit a bit deeper, as if Babel isn't afraid to start digging into more personal themes. That doesn't mean they aren't still tragic ("The Story of My Dovecote", which has bodies where bodies are not expected) and over time there's a sense of progression, as if the narrator is telling the story of his own life in bits and pieces. Most of them have their moments . . . I liked "The First Fee" where the narrator gets a lesson from a prostitute, mostly due to the sense of two damaged people learning how to live with being damaged. But with the stories stretching out a bit more, Babel gets the chance to let events play out a bit more without the need to compress all the action and drama into four pages. I don't know if it makes for a richer experience compared to the others, but its different in a good way.<br /><br />As mentioned the collection gets rounded out by some fragments of manuscripts of stories he planned on writing, which only serves to drive home how tragic and completely unnecessary his death was. Only 45 when he was executed its an open question what he would have done with another twenty or thirty years ahead of him, years he would have eagerly taken if given the chance. Fortunately his writings have been collected and reprinted, rescued from the obscurity that the Soviet government of the time sought to bury forever, and now reading him is as easy as going to the bookstore. The fact that you can even hold his works in your hands and read them is a testament to his family and friends keeping his name alive and in its own way a tribute to so many others who were unjustifiably executed, who might have had their own stories to tell and art to create if given the chance. The loss is tangible, hundreds of pages seemingly not enough, but if there were any justice we'd have a room of shelves for everything that was lost, that was snuffed out without any hope of being regained. Instead, we have this. It’s a small light but sometimes that all you need to be reminded that you haven't gone blind.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8130944186539469184" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


