        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1050131728" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2069002411168989958">Isaac Babel was a famous Russian short story writer who published a handful of collections before being executed in one of Stalin&apos;s purges in 1940. This collection is, I think, all of the short stories he ever published (along with some that he didn&apos;t and were discovered posthumously). It&apos;s an impressive collection, nearly 100 stories in all.<br/><br/>I read this in parallel with Winesburg, Ohio - because why read one ancient collection of short stories when you can read two? I suppose my biggest problem </span>
  <span id="freeText2069002411168989958" style="display:none">Isaac Babel was a famous Russian short story writer who published a handful of collections before being executed in one of Stalin's purges in 1940. This collection is, I think, all of the short stories he ever published (along with some that he didn't and were discovered posthumously). It's an impressive collection, nearly 100 stories in all.<br /><br />I read this in parallel with Winesburg, Ohio - because why read one ancient collection of short stories when you can read two? I suppose my biggest problem here is that so much of this material is unrelatable to me. About a third of these tales are his Red Cavalry stories, written about the 1920 Russian-Polish war, and honestly I didn't get anything out of them other than war is unpleasant, and a lot of horses died. I've read some really good writing on the subject of war, and this doesn't stack up.<br /><br />The best stories here are from the later days of Babel's life - I really enjoyed The Awakening and In the Basement. That said, the great majority of these are in the vein of "Here's a thing that happened to somebody in Odessa in 1921", and I just didn't really care, the writing isn't transcendent to me. Maybe I'm missing the boat w/ Babel, but in retrospect there's plenty of other Russian literature I wish I'd delved into in lieu of this.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2069002411168989958" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
