<span id="freeTextContainer5173991589187818795">The actual version I read was the New American Library paperback published in 1955 with translations by Walter Morrison and an introduction by Lionel Trilling. <br/><br/>The works of Isaac Babel stand among the great writing of the twentieth century. The collections Red Cavalry and Tales of Odessa along with a number of additional stories are breathtaking, disturbing, and moving creations that challenge all easy understandings of the nature of revolution, of war, of human nature and are utterly unique bot</span>
  <span id="freeText5173991589187818795" style="display:none">The actual version I read was the New American Library paperback published in 1955 with translations by Walter Morrison and an introduction by Lionel Trilling. <br /><br />The works of Isaac Babel stand among the great writing of the twentieth century. The collections Red Cavalry and Tales of Odessa along with a number of additional stories are breathtaking, disturbing, and moving creations that challenge all easy understandings of the nature of revolution, of war, of human nature and are utterly unique both in their artistry and their deep understanding of the chaos of modern life. They provide complex and startling insights into the worlds of early twentieth century Jews in Odessa in pre-revolutionary Russia and of the Cossack warriors fighting in Poland for the revolution after 1917. Babel is truly one of our finest writers - up there with the pantheon of the Russians from the late 19th and early 20th centuries, up there with the finest Jewish writers of modernity. <br /><br />My only quibble is with the translation that can vary from brilliance to occasional clunkiness. But I cannot read the original so will have to look at some of the more recent translations to truly be able to judge.</span>
