<div id="review_2761622947" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2761622947" />
    <a title="Rgoldenberg" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29977167-rgoldenberg"><img alt="Rgoldenberg" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1409847092p2/29977167.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2761622947?book_show_action=true">Apr 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rgoldenberg" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rgoldenberg" href="/user/show/29977167-rgoldenberg">Rgoldenberg</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29977167-rgoldenberg?shelf=short-stories">short-stories</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2761622947" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2026808184721692617">I read the following stories from this collection: &quot;The Public Library&quot; (from Early Stories); &quot;How Things Were Done in Odessa&quot; and Lyubka the Cossack&quot; (from The Odessa stories); &quot;Crossing the River Zbrucz&quot; and &quot;My First Goose&quot; (from the Red Cavalry stories); &quot;The Story of my Dovecote,&quot; &quot;First Love,&quot; &quot;The Awakening,&quot; &quot;In the Basement,&quot; &quot;Guy De Maupassant,&quot; and &quot;Di Grasso&quot; (from Stories 1925-1938).<br/><br/>I read only a selection of stories from this collection and I would like to go back to this book one </span>
  <span id="freeText2026808184721692617" style="display:none">I read the following stories from this collection: "The Public Library" (from Early Stories); "How Things Were Done in Odessa" and Lyubka the Cossack" (from The Odessa stories); "Crossing the River Zbrucz" and "My First Goose" (from the Red Cavalry stories); "The Story of my Dovecote," "First Love," "The Awakening," "In the Basement," "Guy De Maupassant," and "Di Grasso" (from Stories 1925-1938).<br /><br />I read only a selection of stories from this collection and I would like to go back to this book one day and read the entire collection of stories to get a fuller grasp of Babel's vision. The pieces that I was most fascinated with were the four semi-autobiographical ones that gave me a window into what life was like for Babel and Jewish families in Odessa just after the turn in the century: "The Story of my Dovecote," "First Love," "The Awakening," "In the Basement." <br /><br />There is a complexity of elements that Babel utilizes including, brutal realism, satiric comedy, and ornamental descriptive prose. Sometimes it's difficult to tell if Babel is being sharply, sometimes shockingly, realistic or exaggerating for effect. His spare style forces a careful reading. I found Professor Donald M. Fiene's (University of Tennessee at Knoxville) essays on Babel's stories highly insightful, especially on how Babel often employs subtle religious symbols and imagery (accessible through Salem Press: Master Plots II, Short Stories). </span>
  <a data-text-id="2026808184721692617" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

