<div id="review_3442255909" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3442255909" />
    <a title="David Smith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5874857-david-smith"><img alt="David Smith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1311582027p2/5874857.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3442255909?book_show_action=true">Jul 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Smith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Smith" href="/user/show/5874857-david-smith">David Smith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/22294697-isaac-babel-the-collected-stories">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3442255909" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16044599395321429008">Caroline gave me this book. I don&apos;t remember her last name, but I met her when we were both 17. It was at the Université du Québec a Chicoutimi. Both of us lived in Montreal. Her father was a general in the Canadian armed forces. She was a communist. I had told her about a branch of my family that comes from Odessa.<br/><br/>She invited to me her place on Emery St, just around the corner from the Faubourg St-Denis, in a flat that could have been the setting for part of Yves Beauchemin&apos;s novel Le Matou (ma</span>
  <span id="freeText16044599395321429008" style="display:none">Caroline gave me this book. I don't remember her last name, but I met her when we were both 17. It was at the Université du Québec a Chicoutimi. Both of us lived in Montreal. Her father was a general in the Canadian armed forces. She was a communist. I had told her about a branch of my family that comes from Odessa.<br /><br />She invited to me her place on Emery St, just around the corner from the Faubourg St-Denis, in a flat that could have been the setting for part of Yves Beauchemin's novel Le Matou (maybe it was). There she gave me the copy of the Collected Stories of Isaac Babel - the same copy I finished reading a moment ago.<br /><br />I've carried this book with me across three continents, always meaning to read it, but another book would come along at just the wrong time and move Isaac back down to the bottom of the pile. In the early days, I think that perhaps Caroline's interest in me not extending beyond political discussions may have had something to do with me pushing the book aside.<br /><br />I have always wanted to visit Odessa. Now, even more. Perhaps the closest thing to being there is reading Isaac Babel - he brings to ones eyes not only the view, but the smell, the feeling of being there, of riding with the Cossacks into Poland, hearing Chaliapin's unmistakable voice, being part of the great transitional period of the early 20th century. I know my grandfather a bit better now.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16044599395321429008" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


