<div id="review_4011733007" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4011733007" />
    <a title="Ben" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73170808-ben"><img alt="Ben" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4011733007?book_show_action=true">May 20, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben" href="/user/show/73170808-ben">Ben</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4011733007" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16276793347289161419">Isaac Babel writes prose in a fascinating way. Or at least it seems that way from this collection of stories translated by Peter Constantine. He uses metaphors and descriptors in a completely unexpected and often almost grotesque way that is very compelling. And while his stories are usually short (even for a short story collection) there is often more substance packed into them than in whole novels. This may be somewhat of an exaggeration, but it was almost convincing as I read through some of </span>
  <span id="freeText16276793347289161419" style="display:none">Isaac Babel writes prose in a fascinating way. Or at least it seems that way from this collection of stories translated by Peter Constantine. He uses metaphors and descriptors in a completely unexpected and often almost grotesque way that is very compelling. And while his stories are usually short (even for a short story collection) there is often more substance packed into them than in whole novels. This may be somewhat of an exaggeration, but it was almost convincing as I read through some of the meatier and more interesting stories. Some of these stories rattled around inside my head for days after I read them, and I mark that as the sign of a good book. That being said, many of the stories feel like they require a somewhat deep knowledge of early Soviet history to be fully appreciated, and some feel like mere trifles. But the bombs in this collection definitely make it worth trudging through the duds.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16276793347289161419" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


